{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_017fDsFksC6dFDQfjhsDX3ZT","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the setup:\n1. The `es-http-tls` secret contains `ca.crt`, `tls.crt`, and `tls.key`\n2. These are mounted into the pods at `/usr/share/elasticsearch/config/certs/`\n3. Elasticsearch uses them for both HTTP SSL and transport SSL\n\nTo rotate the certificates with ~1 year validity:\n1. Generate a new CA key and certificate (365 days)\n2. Generate a new leaf certificate signed by the new CA (365 days) with the same SANs as the current cert\n3. Update the `es-http-tls` secret with the new certificates, then trigger a rolling restart of the StatefulSet so the pods load the updated certs and verify Elasticsearch remains accessible. The SANs need to cover localhost, the service DNS names across the cluster, and the individual pod FQDNs for all three nodes.\n\nNow I'm generating fresh CA and leaf certificates, then executing a rolling restart with kubectl to minimize downtime while the pods pick up the new credentials one at a time.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1310,"cache_read_input_tokens":38037,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1310},"output_tokens":33,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c46df5ca-d802-4421-98fc-98d1f774e7fd","uuid":"ab66b2b5-af7e-4944-bb5f-ec298135f007","request_id":"req_011CccJpMnHwpbbEPxLwA6Sy"}
